// Valuation (6) + Financial Statement Analysis (6) + Credit Analysis (5) = 17 topics
import type { FoundationContent } from "./foundationsContentPart1";

const part2: Record<string, FoundationContent> = {

  // ── VALUATION ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  "dcf-theory-and-mechanics": {
    readingTime: "12 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Time Value of Money", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/time-value-of-money" },
      { label: "Cost of Capital", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/cost-of-capital" },
      { label: "Reading a Cash Flow Statement", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-cash-flow-statement" },
    ],
    intuition: `A DCF (Discounted Cash Flow) model is the most principled way to value a business. The idea is simple: a company is worth the present value of all the cash it will ever generate for its owners. You estimate future free cash flows, choose a discount rate that reflects the riskiness of those cash flows, and discount them back to today.\n\nThis sounds straightforward but involves dozens of assumptions — revenue growth, margins, capex intensity, working capital, terminal growth rate, and WACC. Because the terminal value (the value beyond the explicit forecast period) typically represents 60–80% of total value, the model is enormously sensitive to that single assumption.\n\nDCF is best used not to arrive at a single precise number, but to understand the implied assumptions of the current market price and to stress-test scenarios. When a stock is trading at a price that requires heroic growth assumptions to justify in a DCF, that's informative even if you never know the "right" intrinsic value.`,
    mechanics: `**Two approaches: FCFF and FCFE**\n\n**Free Cash Flow to Firm (FCFF)** — cash available to all capital providers:\n\`FCFF = EBIT × (1 − t) + D&A − Capex − ΔWCE\`\n(ΔWCE = change in operating working capital)\nDiscount FCFF at WACC. Subtract net debt to get equity value.\n\n**Free Cash Flow to Equity (FCFE)** — cash available to equity holders:\n\`FCFE = PAT + D&A − Capex − ΔWCE − Debt Repayment + New Borrowings\`\nDiscount FCFE at cost of equity (Ke). Gives equity value directly.\n\n**Building the model:**\n1. Forecast revenue (volume × price, or segment-by-segment)\n2. Project margins → EBIT\n3. Compute FCFF for each year (typically 5–10 years explicit forecast)\n4. Calculate Terminal Value:\n   - Gordon Growth: \`TV = FCFF_{n+1} ÷ (WACC − g)\`\n   - Exit Multiple: \`TV = EBITDA_n × EV/EBITDA multiple\`\n5. Discount all cash flows + TV at WACC\n6. Add non-operating assets, subtract net debt → Equity Value → divide by shares → intrinsic value per share\n\n**Sensitivity table:** Always output a WACC vs terminal growth rate sensitivity table. Value estimates should span a range, not a single number.`,
    deepDive: `**Two-stage and three-stage models:** A two-stage model has a high-growth period (explicit forecast) followed by stable growth (terminal value). A three-stage model adds a transition period where growth decelerates gradually. Three-stage is more realistic for companies currently in hyper-growth.\n\n**Dilution from ESOPs:** If the company has outstanding employee stock options, add the diluted shares (using the treasury stock method) to the denominator. Ignoring this overstates per-share value for ESOP-heavy technology companies.\n\n**Circular reference in WACC:** WACC uses target capital structure weights (market cap of equity, market value of debt). But market cap of equity is the output of the DCF. This circularity is typically handled by: (a) using current market cap as starting weights and iterating, or (b) using industry-average capital structure.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Using a terminal growth rate above long-run nominal GDP growth. A company cannot grow faster than the economy forever — at some point it would be larger than the economy. For India, a terminal g above 6–7% is generally not defensible.",
      "Double-counting the tax shield. If you've already reduced WACC using after-tax cost of debt (the standard approach), don't also add PV of tax shields separately. Choose one method: WACC approach or APV approach.",
      "Not stress-testing the terminal value assumption. A 0.5% change in terminal growth rate or WACC can shift equity value by 20–30%. A DCF without a sensitivity table is an incomplete analysis.",
    ],
    tryItHref: "/tools/dcf-sensitivity",
  },

  "relative-valuation": {
    readingTime: "10 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading an Income Statement", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-an-income-statement" },
      { label: "Reading a Balance Sheet", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-balance-sheet" },
    ],
    intuition: `Relative valuation prices a company by comparing it to similar companies or recent transactions. Rather than estimating the intrinsic value from first principles, you ask: what are other businesses like this selling for, and does this company look cheap or expensive relative to them?\n\nIt's like pricing a flat in a Mumbai suburb by looking at recent comparable sales rather than computing the net present value of future rental income. Faster, more intuitive, and anchored to what the market is actually paying.\n\nThe limitation is that the entire peer group may be mispriced. In a frothy market, even a "cheap" stock on a relative basis may be expensive in absolute terms. Relative valuation tells you where a company stands in the pack, not whether the pack's pricing makes sense.`,
    mechanics: `**Common multiples and their uses:**\n\n**P/E (Price-to-Earnings)**\n\`P/E = Market Price per Share ÷ EPS\`\nMost widely used. Suitable for profitable, mature companies. Can be trailing (last 12 months EPS) or forward (next 12 months consensus estimate). Doesn't work for loss-making companies.\n\n**EV/EBITDA**\n\`EV = Market Cap + Net Debt + Minority Interest − Associate Value\`\n\`EV/EBITDA = Enterprise Value ÷ EBITDA\`\nCapital-structure neutral — great for comparing companies with different leverage. Most useful for industrial, consumer, and media companies.\n\n**P/B (Price-to-Book)**\n\`P/B = Market Cap ÷ Net Worth (Book Value of Equity)\`\nUsed for banks, NBFCs, and capital-intensive businesses. Meaningless for asset-light businesses with low book value.\n\n**EV/Sales**\nUsed when earnings are negative or highly variable (high-growth startups, cyclical troughs). A blunt instrument.\n\n**When to use which:**\n- Software / IT services: EV/Sales, EV/EBITDA, P/E\n- Banks / NBFCs: P/B, P/E\n- Infrastructure / capital-heavy: EV/EBITDA\n- Cyclical at trough: EV/Sales or EV/replacement cost`,
    deepDive: `**Why peers trade at different multiples:** A higher P/E is usually justified by higher expected growth, higher return on equity, or lower risk. Simply buying the "cheapest" P/E stock in a sector without understanding why it's cheap is a value trap. Decompose the multiple: P/E = (Payout × P/E_justified) = f(growth, ROE, risk).\n\n**Trailing vs Forward:** Forward multiples require earnings estimates, which embed analyst forecasts and their associated error. In earnings-volatile sectors (commodities, banking during credit cycles), forward estimates can be badly wrong. Normalised earnings (average over a full cycle) often give a better base.\n\n**Transaction multiples vs trading multiples:** In M&A contexts, transaction multiples (what an acquirer paid) include a control premium (typically 20–30% over market price). When using precedent transactions for valuation, this premium is already embedded.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Comparing multiples across sectors. A P/E of 15× is expensive for a slow-growing FMCG distributor and cheap for a fast-growing specialty chemical company. Multiples only mean something within a relevant peer group.",
      "Ignoring the denominator quality. A P/E of 10× looks cheap, but if the earnings include large one-off gains or are inflated by aggressive accounting, the clean P/E may be 18×. Always verify denominator quality before calling something cheap.",
      "Picking self-serving comparable companies. Selecting only the highest-multiple peers to justify a high valuation (or the lowest-multiple peers to argue for cheapness) is a common analytical bias. The peer set should be selected on objective criteria: similar business model, size, geography, and growth profile.",
    ],
  },

  "sum-of-the-parts": {
    readingTime: "8 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "DCF: Theory and Mechanics", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/dcf-theory-and-mechanics" },
      { label: "Relative Valuation", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/relative-valuation" },
    ],
    intuition: `Some companies operate multiple, very different businesses — a conglomerate might own a cement plant, a hospitality chain, and a financial services arm. Valuing the whole entity with a single multiple or DCF is inappropriate because each segment has a different risk profile, growth rate, and appropriate comparable set.\n\nSum-of-the-parts (SOTP) valuation solves this by valuing each segment independently using the most relevant method, then adding them up. The equity value is then the sum of segment values minus consolidated net debt at the holding company level.\n\nSOTP is the standard framework for analysing Indian conglomerates like the Tata Group entities, Bajaj Holdings, Aditya Birla Group companies, or diversified infrastructure players. It's also used when a company has significant listed or unlisted subsidiary stakes.`,
    mechanics: `**SOTP Framework:**\n\n1. **Identify segments:** Use Ind AS 108 segment disclosures. Separate operating segments (cement, hotels, finance) from associate/subsidiary stakes.\n\n2. **Value each segment independently:**\n   - Operating segments: DCF or EV/EBITDA (using relevant sector peers)\n   - Listed subsidiary stakes: Market value of stake (% held × market cap of subsidiary)\n   - Unlisted subsidiaries: DCF or P/B\n   - Real estate / land: Separate realisable value estimate\n\n3. **Sum segment values = Enterprise Value of the conglomerate**\n\n4. **Subtract:** Holding company-level net debt and unallocated central costs (capitalised)\n\n5. **= Equity Value → divide by shares → value per share**\n\n**Conglomerate / Holdco Discount:**\nMarket price of a conglomerate often trades below its SOTP value. This "holdco discount" arises from:\n- Illiquidity of unlisted stakes\n- Complexity discount (investors prefer pure plays)\n- Concerns about capital allocation\n- Cross-holdings (A owns B, B owns A — double-counting risk)\nTypical Indian holdco discounts range from 20–50%.`,
    deepDive: `**Avoiding double-counting:** When a parent company owns 60% of a listed subsidiary, the consolidated financial statements already include 100% of the subsidiary's financials (with 40% minority interest). If you're valuing segments from consolidated EBITDA, you've already captured the subsidiary. Don't also add 60% × subsidiary market cap separately.\n\n**Central costs:** Holding companies incur overhead that isn't allocated to segments (CEO compensation, HO rent, compliance costs). These perpetual costs need to be capitalised (typically at 10–15× the annual cost) and subtracted from SOTP value.\n\n**When SOTP is most useful:** For conglomerates where a fast-growing segment is hidden inside a slower parent (e.g., a tech business inside a traditional conglomerate). SOTP can surface the hidden value.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Double-counting subsidiaries. If segment EBITDA already includes a subsidiary's profit (consolidated P&L), adding the market value of that subsidiary's stake on top is double-counting. Be clear about whether you're starting from standalone or consolidated financials.",
      "Applying the wrong segment multiple. Using IT sector EV/EBITDA multiples for a technology services division of a diversified conglomerate that has captive revenue streams will overstate value.",
      "Ignoring the holdco discount. Even if SOTP gives ₹500 per share, a holding company may trade at ₹350 due to structural discounts. The discount is real and reflects genuine risk and illiquidity.",
    ],
  },

  "sector-specific-valuation": {
    readingTime: "11 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "DCF: Theory and Mechanics", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/dcf-theory-and-mechanics" },
      { label: "Relative Valuation", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/relative-valuation" },
      { label: "Cost of Capital", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/cost-of-capital" },
    ],
    intuition: `The same valuation multiple applied to a bank and a software company would be meaningless. Different industries have fundamentally different economics — how they use assets, how they earn returns, what risks they face, and what drives long-term value. Standard EBITDA-based frameworks break down for financials because debt is an operating input for banks, not just a financing choice.\n\nLearning sector-specific valuation frameworks is a prerequisite for serious equity analysis. An analyst covering HDFC Bank needs to think in terms of Net Interest Margin, Return on Assets, and Price-to-Book — not EV/EBITDA. An analyst covering an insurance company needs to understand embedded value and value of new business (VNB).\n\nIndia's listed equity market is heavily weighted toward financials, which makes understanding bank and NBFC valuation particularly important.`,
    mechanics: `**Banks and NBFCs:**\n- **Primary metrics:** NIM (Net Interest Margin), GNPA (Gross Non-Performing Assets) %, PCR (Provision Coverage Ratio), ROA, ROE\n- **Primary multiple:** P/BV (Price-to-Book Value) — justified by ROE: \`Justified P/BV = (ROE − g) ÷ (Ke − g)\`\n- **NEVER use EV/EBITDA for banks** — debt is an operating input, not just capital structure\n- Gordon Growth: Equity value = Book Value × P/BV multiple\n\n**Insurance Companies:**\n- Valuation basis: Embedded Value (EV) = Net Asset Value + Value in Force (VIF)\n- VIF = PV of future profits from existing policy book\n- Key multiple: P/EV and P/VNB (Price to Value of New Business annualised)\n- Growth driver: VNB Margin = VNB ÷ Annualised Premium Equivalent (APE)\n\n**Real Estate:**\n- Listed developers: NAV-based (Net Asset Value = GDV of projects − construction costs − net debt)\n- GDV = Gross Development Value (saleable area × expected realisation)\n- REITs: Yield-based (Distribution yield, cap rate)\n\n**Oil & Gas / Commodity:**\n- EV/2P Reserves, EV/EBITDA at mid-cycle prices\n- Strip pricing DCF: discount cash flows at forward commodity curve\n\n**Telecom:**\n- EV/EBITDA, EV/Subscriber; ARPU growth is the key revenue driver`,
    deepDive: `**DuPont decomposition for banks:** Bank ROE = ROA × Leverage (Assets/Equity). High ROE can reflect either superior profitability (good) or excessive leverage (risky). Decompose before concluding a bank is high-quality.\n\n**Credit cycle sensitivity:** Bank P/BV multiples compress during credit stress cycles when GNPA rises and provisions eat into book value. Historical Indian banking crises (2015–18 NPA cycle) saw several PSU banks trade below book value for years.\n\n**Sector-specific risk adjustments:** In WACC, you need a beta that reflects sector risk. Financial sector betas in India tend to be above 1.0 (cyclical, leveraged). Real estate developer betas are high (project execution risk, leverage). Utility betas are typically below 1.0 (regulated returns, stable cash flows).`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Applying EV/EBITDA to banks or NBFCs. Borrowings are a core operating input for financial intermediaries. Adding debt to get enterprise value — and then comparing to pre-provision profits — conflates operating and financing items in a way that's analytically invalid.",
      "Using book value multiples for asset-light businesses. A technology company or a hospital chain can have very high ROE on a thin equity base. P/BV tells you nothing useful here; P/E and DCF are far more informative.",
      "Extrapolating a bank's peak ROA as normalised. During low-credit-cost years, banks can show high ROA. When the credit cycle turns and provisions rise, ROA collapses. Always normalise for credit costs before applying a P/BV multiple.",
    ],
  },

  "terminal-value-approaches": {
    readingTime: "9 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "DCF: Theory and Mechanics", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/dcf-theory-and-mechanics" },
      { label: "Time Value of Money", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/time-value-of-money" },
    ],
    intuition: `In most DCF models, the terminal value — the value attributed to cash flows beyond the explicit forecast period — accounts for 60–80% of total enterprise value. This means that despite spending hours forecasting five or ten years of detailed cash flows, the result is dominated by a single, hard-to-estimate number.\n\nThis is simultaneously DCF's greatest strength and its most dangerous weakness. The strength: it forces analysts to articulate what long-run growth and profitability they're assuming. The weakness: small changes to these assumptions produce dramatic swings in value, making precision illusory.\n\nThere are two main approaches: the Gordon Growth Model (perpetuity assumption) and the Exit Multiple method (what would a rational buyer pay for this business in year n?). Both require judgment, and the best analysts use both as cross-checks.`,
    mechanics: `**Method 1: Gordon Growth Model (Perpetuity Growth)**\n\`TV = FCFF_{n+1} ÷ (WACC − g)\`\nWhere g = long-run perpetuity growth rate.\n\n- FCFFₙ₊₁ = FCFFₙ × (1 + g)\n- g must be less than WACC (otherwise TV → ∞)\n- For India: g typically 4–7% in nominal terms (long-run GDP growth range)\n\n**Reinvestment rate check:**\n\`g = Reinvestment Rate × ROIC\`\nIf you assume g = 6% and ROIC = 15% in perpetuity, the implied reinvestment rate = 40%. Check: does this make sense for a mature business?\n\n**Method 2: Exit Multiple**\n\`TV = EBITDA_n × EV/EBITDA exit multiple\`\nThe exit multiple should reflect what a buyer would pay for a mature, stable version of this business. Use current trading multiples of comparable mature companies in the sector.\n\n**Cross-check:** Given your exit-multiple-derived TV, back-solve for the implied perpetuity growth rate. If the exit multiple implies g = 9% when you're using WACC of 11% and India's long-run GDP is 6–7%, something is inconsistent.`,
    deepDive: `**FCFF in terminal year must reflect steady-state:** The terminal year FCFF should assume a normalised capex (sufficient to support only the growth rate g), not the high-growth capex of the explicit forecast period. A common error is to carry heavy growth capex into terminal value, which simultaneously assumes high capex and low cash flow while also assuming high growth — that's circular.\n\n**Negative WACC−g scenarios:** If the risk-free rate collapses (as it did globally post-2008), WACC can approach the assumed terminal growth rate, making terminal value extremely sensitive. This is one reason low-rate environments produce apparently sky-high equity valuations.\n\n**Horizon value sensitivity:** Extending the explicit forecast from 5 to 10 years reduces the weight of TV in total value — but only if the company is growing in the forecast period. If the company is already in steady state, the horizon length doesn't matter much.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Using a terminal growth rate above nominal GDP growth. India's long-run nominal GDP growth is roughly 10–12% (6–7% real + ~5% inflation). A company cannot grow faster than the economy in perpetuity — it would eventually be larger than the entire economy.",
      "Applying an exit multiple that reflects today's frothy valuations. If you're doing a DCF of a company in 2025 using a 30× EV/EBITDA exit multiple because that's where peers trade today, you're embedding today's market sentiment into a 5-year-forward assumption. Use normalised, mid-cycle multiples instead.",
      "Not checking the reinvestment rate implied by your terminal value. If your terminal ROIC is 20% and your growth rate is 6%, you need only 30% reinvestment rate. If your FCFF margin implies only 10% reinvestment but growth is 8%, the math doesn't work — the company can't grow that fast without investing.",
    ],
  },

  "common-dcf-mistakes": {
    readingTime: "8 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "DCF: Theory and Mechanics", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/dcf-theory-and-mechanics" },
      { label: "Terminal Value Approaches", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/terminal-value-approaches" },
      { label: "Cost of Capital", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/cost-of-capital" },
    ],
    intuition: `DCF is the most rigorous valuation framework — and the most abused. Because it accepts any inputs you choose, it can be used to "prove" almost any valuation you want. The same DCF model can justify ₹500 or ₹2,000 per share depending on what assumptions the analyst makes — or is incentivised to make.\n\nMost DCF errors fall into three categories: mechanical errors (wrong formula, wrong sign), assumption errors (inputs don't reflect economic reality), and conceptual errors (wrong framework for the situation). Understanding the failure modes makes you a better analyst of others' models and a more rigorous builder of your own.\n\nThe most important discipline: always reverse-engineer the market price. Instead of computing an intrinsic value and comparing to market, ask "what assumptions does the current market price require?" Then judge whether those assumptions are realistic.`,
    mechanics: `**Ten common DCF mistakes:**\n\n1. **Terminal growth rate > WACC.** TV = FCFF ÷ (WACC − g). If g ≥ WACC, terminal value blows up to infinity. This is mathematically and economically wrong.\n\n2. **Using unadjusted reported FCFF** without stripping working capital distortions, exceptional items, or one-off capex.\n\n3. **Not adjusting WACC for changing capital structure** over the forecast period. A company that's deleveraging rapidly has a different risk profile in year 10 vs year 1.\n\n4. **Discounting at mid-period vs end-of-period** without consistency. Mid-period discounting (cash flows received throughout the year) is more realistic but must be applied consistently.\n\n5. **Double-counting the tax shield.** If using WACC (which uses after-tax Kd), don't also add the PV of tax shields separately.\n\n6. **Forgetting minority interest / associates.** EV from DCF is for the whole enterprise. Must add associate values and subtract minority interest and net debt to get equity value.\n\n7. **Stale beta.** Using a 5-year monthly beta from a period when the company's business has fundamentally changed.\n\n8. **Not stress-testing.** A DCF without a sensitivity table (WACC × g) is incomplete.\n\n9. **Anchoring to the current stock price.** The goal is independent analysis. If your model keeps "coming out" near the current price, check whether you're unconsciously fitting inputs to justify it.\n\n10. **Treating DCF output as precise.** A value range (e.g., ₹800–₹1,200) is more honest and useful than a single point estimate.`,
    deepDive: `**Circularity:** WACC requires market cap for weights, but market cap is the DCF output. Handle this by iterating (Solver in Excel), using the current market cap as starting weights and solving until stable, or using industry-average capital structure.\n\n**When DCF breaks down:** DCF is not appropriate for: early-stage companies with no visible path to cash flow, distressed companies where going-concern value is in question, financial companies (banks — use DDM or excess return models), or holding companies (use SOTP).\n\n**The "Excel jockey" risk:** A technically perfect DCF with garbage assumptions is still garbage. The hard part is the economics — what really drives revenue growth, what's a sustainable margin, what ROIC will the business earn in maturity. Excel mechanics are teachable; business judgment is earned over years.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Building precision into an inherently uncertain exercise. Forecasting 10 years of cash flows to two decimal places implies a false precision. Wide scenario ranges (bear/base/bull) are more intellectually honest than a single detailed projection.",
      "Ignoring inflation consistency. If you project revenues in real terms (volume growth without price), you must discount at a real discount rate, not nominal. Mixing nominal cash flows with real rates (or vice versa) systematically mis-states NPV.",
      "Working backwards from the answer. An investment bank pitching an acquisition will often build a DCF that justifies the client's target price. Recognise this bias when reading sell-side and M&A DCFs — the answer preceded the model.",
    ],
  },

  // ── FINANCIAL STATEMENT ANALYSIS ───────────────────────────────────────────

  "profitability-ratios": {
    readingTime: "9 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading an Income Statement", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-an-income-statement" },
      { label: "Reading a Balance Sheet", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-balance-sheet" },
    ],
    intuition: `Profitability ratios answer the question: how efficiently is the company converting inputs into profit? They can be computed at different levels of the P&L (gross, operating, net) and at the level of the balance sheet (how much return on capital deployed).\n\nMargin ratios (gross margin, EBITDA margin, PAT margin) show operating efficiency — what percentage of every rupee of revenue survives as profit. Return ratios (ROE, ROA, ROCE) show capital efficiency — how much profit is generated per rupee of capital employed.\n\nFor an equity investor, return ratios are ultimately more important than margin ratios. A company with low margins but very high asset turnover can generate excellent returns on capital. The textile and trading businesses often work this way — thin margins, fast inventory turns, strong ROCE.`,
    mechanics: `**Margin ratios:**\n\n- **Gross Profit Margin = Gross Profit ÷ Revenue** — Reflects pricing power and input cost management\n- **EBITDA Margin = EBITDA ÷ Revenue** — Operating efficiency before financing and depreciation\n- **EBIT Margin = EBIT ÷ Revenue** — Reflects D&A intensity (higher for capital-heavy businesses)\n- **PAT Margin = PAT ÷ Revenue** — Bottom-line efficiency after all costs\n\n**Return ratios:**\n\n- **ROE = PAT ÷ Average Shareholders' Equity** — Return on shareholders' investment. Sustainable ROE > cost of equity creates value.\n- **ROA = PAT ÷ Average Total Assets** — Overall asset efficiency. Key for banks (typical range: 1–2% for good Indian banks).\n- **ROCE = EBIT × (1−t) ÷ Average Capital Employed** — Return on all capital (equity + debt). \`Capital Employed = Total Assets − Current Liabilities\`. Best for comparing capital intensity across companies.\n- **ROIC = NOPAT ÷ Invested Capital** — \`NOPAT = EBIT × (1−t)\`. Most precise for economic value analysis.`,
    deepDive: `**Economic Value Added (EVA):** \`EVA = NOPAT − (WACC × Invested Capital)\`. Positive EVA means the company earned above its cost of capital — it created economic value, not just accounting profit. Companies trading at high P/B multiples typically generate consistently positive EVA.\n\n**ROE inflation via leverage:** A company that earns 10% ROA on assets financed 50% by debt at 7% after-tax will show ROE of ~13%. Increasing leverage to 70% debt raises ROE to ~18% — but without any improvement in underlying operations. Always decompose ROE into its drivers (DuPont).\n\n**Sector benchmarks for India (illustrative ranges):** IT services EBITDA margin: 20–30%. FMCG: 15–25%. Pharma: 15–25%. Metals: highly cyclical. Banks: ROA 1–2%; ROE 12–18%. Cement: EBITDA/tonne and margins driven by regional supply-demand.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Comparing margins across sectors without context. A 10% PAT margin is impressive for a retailer and mediocre for a pharmaceutical company. Always benchmark within the sector and against the company's own history.",
      "Using period-end equity for ROE instead of average equity. If a company raised large equity mid-year, period-end equity overstates the capital that was working for the full year. Use average (opening + closing ÷ 2).",
      "Confusing ROCE and ROE. ROCE includes debt capital; ROE is equity only. A company with high leverage may have high ROE but poor ROCE — it is using financial leverage, not operational superiority, to generate returns.",
    ],
  },

  "liquidity-ratios": {
    readingTime: "6 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading a Balance Sheet", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-balance-sheet" },
      { label: "Working Capital", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/working-capital" },
    ],
    intuition: `Liquidity ratios answer: can this company pay its bills in the short run? A company can be profitable on paper and still run out of cash if it can't convert assets into cash fast enough to meet immediate obligations.\n\nThe 2008 crisis and several high-profile Indian corporate failures (IL&FS in 2018, DHFL in 2019) demonstrated how companies that appeared profitable and even investment-grade rated could suffer rapid liquidity collapse when short-term funding dried up. Liquidity analysis is the first line of distress detection.\n\nLiquidity is distinct from solvency — a company can be technically solvent (assets > liabilities) but still illiquid if its assets are long-dated and illiquid while liabilities are short-dated. This asset-liability mismatch is the core of most financial crises.`,
    mechanics: `**Three standard ratios:**\n\n**Current Ratio = Current Assets ÷ Current Liabilities**\nA ratio above 1.0 means current assets exceed current liabilities. General benchmark: 1.5–2.0× for manufacturing. However, context matters enormously — a retailer like DMart may run below 1.0× comfortably because of its negative working capital model.\n\n**Quick Ratio (Acid Test) = (Current Assets − Inventories) ÷ Current Liabilities**\nMore conservative — removes inventory because it may take time to sell. Benchmark: 1.0× or above.\n\n**Cash Ratio = (Cash + Cash Equivalents + Current Investments) ÷ Current Liabilities**\nThe most conservative. Shows how much immediate cash is available. Very low ratios are fine for stable businesses with committed credit lines; concerning for businesses facing refinancing risk.\n\n**Other liquidity signals:**\n- **Interest Coverage (EBIT ÷ Interest Expense):** Below 1.5× suggests stress\n- **Debt Service Coverage (DSCR = EBITDA ÷ (Interest + Principal Repayment)):** Below 1.0× means the company cannot service debt from operations\n- **Cash burn rate** (for pre-revenue companies): months of runway = Cash ÷ Monthly cash burn`,
    deepDive: `**Operating vs balance sheet liquidity:** Balance sheet liquidity (ratios above) captures current assets vs liabilities. Operating liquidity is whether the business generates sufficient cash from operations to meet its needs. The CFO is the best measure of operating liquidity — a company with low current ratio but strong CFO may be safer than a company with high current ratio but negative CFO.\n\n**Undrawn credit lines:** Balance sheet ratios don't capture committed but undrawn revolving credit facilities, which are a meaningful source of liquidity for large corporations. In credit analysis, available liquidity = cash + undrawn committed facilities.\n\n**Indian-specific risk — commercial paper rollover:** Many Indian NBFCs and corporates relied on short-term commercial paper (CP) for funding long-term assets. IL&FS and DHFL collapsed partly when the CP market froze and they couldn't refinance. Always check the proportion of short-term debt vs total debt.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Treating a current ratio above 2× as universally good. A very high current ratio can indicate excessive idle inventory or slow-collecting receivables — both signs of operational inefficiency, not financial strength.",
      "Ignoring inventory quality in the current ratio. Current ratio includes inventories at cost. If those inventories are obsolete, unsellable, or subject to write-down, the true current ratio is lower than reported.",
      "Relying on static ratios for dynamic situations. Liquidity crises develop fast. A quarterly balance sheet may show comfortable ratios while the company is in the middle of a credit crunch. Real-time indicators (CP market access, stock of liquid investments) are more useful in stress situations.",
    ],
  },

  "solvency-ratios": {
    readingTime: "7 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading a Balance Sheet", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-balance-sheet" },
      { label: "Capital Structure", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/capital-structure" },
    ],
    intuition: `Solvency ratios answer: can this company survive the long run? Is the debt manageable relative to earnings power and asset base? While liquidity ratios focus on the next 12 months, solvency ratios take a multi-year view of financial health.\n\nThe central question in solvency analysis is whether a company can comfortably service its debt through the economic cycle — including during a downturn when revenues fall and credit conditions tighten. A company with a Net Debt/EBITDA of 1.0× has very comfortable headroom; one at 6.0× is in territory where a 30% earnings drop could leave it unable to service debt.\n\nFor equity investors, solvency matters because financial distress is enormously costly. Companies that approach insolvency often raise dilutive equity, sell assets at distressed prices, or lose talent and contracts — destroying value even if they ultimately survive.`,
    mechanics: `**Key solvency ratios:**\n\n**Net Debt / EBITDA**\n\`Net Debt = Gross Borrowings − Cash & Liquid Investments\`\nHow many years of operating earnings to repay net debt. Generally: < 2× comfortable, 2–4× moderate, > 4× elevated risk. For capital-intensive sectors (infra, power), 5–6× can be normal.\n\n**Debt / Equity (D/E)**\n\`D/E = Total Borrowings ÷ Total Equity (Book)\`\nSimple leverage measure. Varies widely by sector. For Indian industrials, < 1× is conservative; 2–3× is moderate leverage.\n\n**Interest Coverage (ICR)**\n\`ICR = EBIT ÷ Finance Costs\`\nA ratio of 3× or above is generally comfortable. Below 1.5× is a stress signal. Investment-grade companies in India typically maintain ICR above 3×.\n\n**Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR)**\n\`DSCR = (EBITDA or CFO) ÷ (Interest + Principal Repayment)\`\nUsed in project finance and bank loan assessments. Below 1.0× means the company cannot service debt from operations — unsustainable.\n\n**Altman Z-Score** (covered in Credit Analysis section) combines solvency and profitability into a distress probability score.`,
    deepDive: `**Lease-adjusted leverage:** Under Ind AS 116, operating leases are capitalised and create both an asset and a liability. When computing leverage for comparison with pre-Ind AS 116 data (or for companies in different lease-intensity sectors), analysts add lease liabilities to net debt.\n\n**Net debt vs gross debt:** A company with ₹5,000 Cr of gross debt and ₹4,500 Cr of cash has very different risk than one with ₹500 Cr of gross debt. For solvency analysis, always use net debt. Exception: cash may be trapped in subsidiaries (restricted cash), in which case use gross debt or haircut the cash.\n\n**Covenant headroom:** Many Indian term loans and NCDs carry financial covenants (e.g., "Net Debt/EBITDA shall not exceed 4.5× tested quarterly"). Headroom to covenant breach matters — a company at 4.0× with a 4.5× covenant has less flexibility than a 1.5× covenant headroom suggests.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Using gross debt when a company holds substantial liquid investments. Net debt/EBITDA is meaningless if a cash-rich company like an IT firm holds ₹30,000 Cr of cash against ₹5,000 Cr of gross borrowings. Gross leverage ratios would be misleading.",
      "Applying uniform leverage benchmarks across sectors. A utility or toll road with contracted revenue streams can comfortably carry 6× Net Debt/EBITDA. A cyclical commodity company at the same leverage would be dangerously over-geared.",
      "Ignoring debt maturity profile. Two companies with identical Net Debt/EBITDA of 3× can have very different risk profiles if one's debt is all due next year while the other's is spread over 10 years. Always review the debt maturity schedule.",
    ],
  },

  "efficiency-ratios": {
    readingTime: "7 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading a Balance Sheet", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-balance-sheet" },
      { label: "Working Capital", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/working-capital" },
    ],
    intuition: `Efficiency ratios measure how productively a company uses its assets to generate revenue. Two companies with the same revenue and the same EBIT margin can have very different asset requirements — one might need ₹100 Cr of assets to generate ₹100 Cr of revenue, while the other needs only ₹50 Cr. The latter is twice as efficient and will generate far higher returns on capital.\n\nIn India, efficiency differences within a sector can be dramatic. In the cement industry, some plants convert raw material to despatch in 25 days; others take 45 days. In pharmaceuticals, API manufacturers with complex molecules take months of WIP inventory; generic formulation companies may have much leaner cycles.\n\nEfficiency analysis tells the story of the operational engine behind the financial results. It complements profitability analysis — you need both dimensions (margin and turnover) to understand ROCE.`,
    mechanics: `**Asset turnover ratios:**\n\n**Total Asset Turnover = Revenue ÷ Average Total Assets**\nHow much revenue per rupee of assets. Asset-light businesses (IT, consulting) turn assets many times. Capital-heavy businesses (steel, cement) have low turnover.\n\n**Fixed Asset Turnover = Revenue ÷ Average Net Fixed Assets**\nUseful for capital-intensive companies. A declining trend suggests assets are ageing and not being replaced, or new capacity isn't generating proportional revenue.\n\n**Working capital efficiency (the cash conversion cycle):**\n\n- **Days Inventory Outstanding (DIO) = (Inventory ÷ COGS) × 365**\n- **Days Sales Outstanding (DSO) = (Trade Receivables ÷ Revenue) × 365**\n- **Days Payable Outstanding (DPO) = (Trade Payables ÷ COGS) × 365**\n- **CCC = DIO + DSO − DPO**\n\n**Capital Efficiency:**\n\n\`ROIC = NOPAT ÷ Invested Capital\` (see profitability ratios)\n\`Asset Intensity = Invested Capital ÷ Revenue\` — lower is better for asset-light business models`,
    deepDive: `**Year-end vs average balances:** Using year-end inventory or receivables for ratio calculation creates seasonal distortion. Use average balances (opening + closing ÷ 2) for any balance sheet-based efficiency ratio.\n\n**Industry benchmarks matter:** DSO of 60 days is tight for a construction company (where large project billing takes time) and alarming for an FMCG distributor. Always compare within the relevant peer group and watch the trend over time.\n\n**The efficiency-profitability trade-off:** Tightening receivables (lower DSO) may require offering shorter credit terms, which can cost sales. Reducing inventory (lower DIO) may cause stockouts and lost revenue. Analysts need to understand whether efficiency improvements are operationally sustainable or achieved by straining commercial relationships.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Using year-end balances instead of averages for ratio calculation. A company that ends its financial year with very high inventory (say, pre-festival stock-up) will show high DIO even if average inventory is lean. Always use average of opening and closing balances.",
      "Computing CCC from total liabilities rather than trade payables for DPO. Only trade payables (amounts owed to suppliers of goods and services) belong in DPO. Short-term debt, advance tax payable, and statutory liabilities are not operational payables.",
      "Ignoring efficiency trends in favour of absolute levels. A DSO of 45 days is fine if the sector average is 50 days. But if it was 30 days two years ago, the rising trend is a warning sign — investigate why customers are taking longer to pay.",
    ],
  },

  "market-ratios": {
    readingTime: "7 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading an Income Statement", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-an-income-statement" },
      { label: "Relative Valuation", href: "/learn/foundations/valuation/relative-valuation" },
    ],
    intuition: `Market ratios combine financial statement data with market prices to express what investors are paying for each unit of earnings, book value, or cash flow. They are the most visible metrics in financial media — the Nifty 50 P/E ratio is published daily and watched by millions.\n\nBut widely watched doesn't mean well understood. A P/E ratio is meaningless without context: is this high-growth or mature? Are earnings cyclically depressed or at a peak? Is the E "clean" or loaded with one-off items? A P/E of 20× for a growing company with sustainable earnings is very different from the same multiple for a cyclical company at the top of the cycle.\n\nMarket ratios are most useful as initial screening tools to identify where to focus attention — not as standalone buy/sell signals.`,
    mechanics: `**Primary market ratios:**\n\n**P/E (Price-to-Earnings)**\n\`P/E = Market Price ÷ Earnings Per Share\`\nTrailing P/E uses last 12 months EPS. Forward P/E uses consensus next-12-months EPS estimate.\nPEG Ratio = P/E ÷ EPS Growth Rate — adjusts for growth. PEG < 1.0× often considered attractive.\n\n**EV/EBITDA**\n\`EV = Market Cap + Net Debt + Minority Interest − Associate Value\`\n\`EV/EBITDA = EV ÷ EBITDA\`\nCapital-structure neutral. Common for M&A and cross-company comparison.\n\n**P/B (Price-to-Book)**\n\`P/B = Market Cap ÷ Net Worth\`\nBelow 1.0× suggests market values the company below liquidation value — either a deep value opportunity or a structural problem.\n\n**Dividend Yield**\n\`Dividend Yield = DPS ÷ Market Price\`\nUseful for income investors. High yield can signal either generous capital return or market pricing in business distress.\n\n**EPS (Earnings Per Share)**\n\`EPS = (PAT − Preference Dividends) ÷ Weighted Average Diluted Shares\`\nDiluted EPS includes shares that would be issued on exercise of options and convertibles.`,
    deepDive: `**Cyclically Adjusted P/E (CAPE / Shiller P/E):** To correct for earnings cyclicality, use average real earnings over 10 years as the denominator. This is more stable than single-year earnings. Applied to the Nifty 50, it gives a better sense of whether the market is cheap or expensive relative to history.\n\n**EV computation nuances:** EV adds minority interest (because it represents a claim on the consolidated enterprise that isn't captured in market cap of the listed parent). It subtracts the value of associates (because associate income is below EBIT, so EBITDA doesn't include associate profits). Getting EV exactly right requires careful reading of the balance sheet.\n\n**Market cap vs enterprise value:** Use market cap-based multiples (P/E, P/B) when the metric is equity-level (EPS, book value of equity). Use EV-based multiples (EV/EBITDA, EV/Sales) when the metric is pre-financing (EBITDA, revenue). Mismatching causes systematic errors.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Comparing trailing P/E with forward P/E across different companies. One company's P/E may be trailing while the peer's is forward. In a year of strong earnings growth, this can make one look much cheaper than it is.",
      "Ignoring net cash in P/B for asset-light companies. A software company with ₹200 Cr net cash and ₹100 Cr of other net assets has a P/B of 2× if shares trade at ₹600 Cr market cap. But strip the cash and the operating business P/B is 4×.",
      "Using headline EPS without checking for dilution. If a company has large outstanding ESOPs, convertible debentures, or warrants, diluted EPS is materially lower than basic EPS. Always use diluted shares for a true P/E.",
    ],
  },

  "dupont-decomposition": {
    readingTime: "8 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Profitability Ratios", href: "/learn/foundations/financial-statement-analysis/profitability-ratios" },
      { label: "Efficiency Ratios", href: "/learn/foundations/financial-statement-analysis/efficiency-ratios" },
      { label: "Solvency Ratios", href: "/learn/foundations/financial-statement-analysis/solvency-ratios" },
    ],
    intuition: `ROE is the most important single metric for an equity investor — it tells you how much the company earned on shareholders' capital. But a high ROE can arise for very different reasons: superior margins, better asset utilisation, or simply higher financial leverage. DuPont decomposition breaks ROE into these components to reveal which driver is responsible.\n\nInvented by DuPont Corporation in the 1920s, this decomposition is as relevant today as it was a century ago. A company with 25% ROE driven by 20% PAT margins and moderate leverage is a very different investment than one with 25% ROE driven by razor-thin margins, massive asset turnover, and 8× leverage.\n\nDecomposing ROE across time (has the driver mix changed?) and across peers (why does Company A have higher ROE than Company B?) provides the most structured framework for comparing businesses.`,
    mechanics: `**Three-factor DuPont:**\n\n\`ROE = Net Profit Margin × Asset Turnover × Financial Leverage\`\n\n\`ROE = (PAT/Revenue) × (Revenue/Assets) × (Assets/Equity)\`\n\nExample: PAT Margin = 10%, Asset Turnover = 1.5×, Leverage = 2.0×\n→ ROE = 10% × 1.5 × 2.0 = **30%**\n\n**Five-factor DuPont (extended):**\n\n\`ROE = Tax Burden × Interest Burden × EBIT Margin × Asset Turnover × Leverage\`\n\n\`ROE = (PAT/PBT) × (PBT/EBIT) × (EBIT/Revenue) × (Revenue/Assets) × (Assets/Equity)\`\n\n- Tax Burden = PAT/PBT (1 − effective tax rate)\n- Interest Burden = PBT/EBIT (reflects cost of debt)\n- EBIT Margin = pure operating profitability\n- Asset Turnover = efficiency\n- Leverage = equity multiplier\n\nThis five-factor version separates the effect of tax management and interest costs from operating profitability — useful when comparing companies across tax jurisdictions or with different financing.`,
    deepDive: `**Cross-sector application:** IT services companies typically have high margins, low turnover (asset-light), and low leverage → ROE driven purely by operating excellence. Banks have thin margins at the net income level, but extremely high leverage (10–12× equity multiplier) → ROE driven by leverage. FMCG companies combine decent margins with moderate asset turnover and low leverage.\n\n**ROE sustainability check:** High ROE × (1 − Dividend Payout) = Sustainable Growth Rate (SGR). A company with 25% ROE that retains 60% of profits can sustainably grow book value at 15% per year. If a company is growing faster than its SGR, it will need to issue equity or take on debt.\n\n**Decomposing change in ROE year-over-year:** If ROE fell from 20% to 15%, which component drove it? If margins compressed while turnover and leverage were stable, investigate cost pressures. If turnover fell, investigate asset utilisation. If leverage declined, the company may have repaid debt (positive sign, but reduces ROE).`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Celebrating ROE driven purely by high leverage. A leveraged buyout can produce 35% ROE on paper; the underlying business might earn only 8% ROCE. Always check whether the leverage that inflates ROE is sustainable or dangerous.",
      "Using ending equity rather than average equity. ROE should use average equity because equity changes throughout the year. For companies that issue significant new equity mid-year, this difference is material.",
      "Ignoring the tax burden and interest burden factors in the five-factor model. A company that appears to have high EBIT margins but low ROE might be paying very high interest or operating in a high-tax environment — the extended DuPont reveals this.",
    ],
  },

  // ── CREDIT ANALYSIS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  "credit-risk-fundamentals": {
    readingTime: "9 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading a Balance Sheet", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-balance-sheet" },
      { label: "Solvency Ratios", href: "/learn/foundations/financial-statement-analysis/solvency-ratios" },
    ],
    intuition: `Credit risk is the risk that a borrower will fail to make promised payments on time. Lenders — banks, bond investors, suppliers extending trade credit — all face this risk every time they extend credit. Unlike equity investors who profit when companies outperform, creditors only care about one thing: getting repaid.\n\nThis asymmetric payoff (fixed upside, potential full loss of principal) drives an entirely different analytical mindset. A creditor asks: what's the worst realistic case? Can the company service debt under stress? What assets can be seized if repayment fails?\n\nIn India, the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC), enacted in 2016, transformed the credit landscape by giving lenders a time-bound resolution mechanism. Pre-IBC, creditors had limited practical recourse. Post-IBC, recovery rates have improved and promoters face real consequences for default — changing how credit risk is priced.`,
    mechanics: `**The 5 Cs of Credit (classic framework):**\n\n1. **Character:** Management integrity, track record of honouring commitments, corporate governance quality\n2. **Capacity:** Ability to generate sufficient cash flow to service debt — DSCR, ICR, FCF\n3. **Capital:** Balance sheet strength — leverage ratios, net worth, tangible assets\n4. **Collateral:** Assets pledged as security — liquidation value vs loan amount\n5. **Conditions:** Industry dynamics, macro environment, competitive position\n\n**Quantitative credit risk framework (Basel/RAROC approach):**\n- **PD (Probability of Default):** Likelihood of default in a given horizon (1 year, 5 year)\n- **LGD (Loss Given Default):** % of exposure lost if default occurs (1 − Recovery Rate)\n- **EAD (Exposure at Default):** Total drawn + undrawn committed amount at default\n- **Expected Loss = PD × LGD × EAD**\n\n**Credit metrics to monitor:**\n- Interest Coverage Ratio (EBIT/Interest) — minimum ~2× for investment grade\n- DSCR (EBITDA or CFO ÷ Debt Service) — > 1.25× required by most lenders\n- Net Debt/EBITDA — key covenant metric\n- FCF after capex — ultimate test of debt serviceability`,
    deepDive: `**Structural vs liquidity default:** Structural default (liabilities > assets, permanently impaired business) is the severe case. Liquidity default (viable business but temporary cash crunch) can be resolved with refinancing. The IBC process is designed to rehabilitate structurally viable companies (resolution plan) and liquidate non-viable ones.\n\n**Secured vs unsecured:** In Indian credit markets, term loans are typically secured on fixed assets. NCDs (Non-Convertible Debentures) can be secured or unsecured. In liquidation, secured creditors have priority over unsecured creditors. The recovery rate for unsecured creditors is historically low in India.\n\n**Credit cycle:** Credit risk expands during economic expansions (loose lending standards, rising leverage) and crystallises during contractions (defaults spike, recovery rates fall). The 2015–18 NPA (Non-Performing Asset) crisis in Indian banking was a classic credit cycle outcome from overextended infrastructure and project finance lending.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Focusing only on financials and ignoring governance and character. Some of India's largest corporate defaults (yes, there have been several) occurred at companies with apparently strong financial ratios — the warning signals were governance red flags: related party transactions, audit qualifications, promoter pledging.",
      "Treating secured lending as risk-free. Security is only as good as the liquidation value of the collateral and the enforceability of the charge. Land and buildings in a distressed sale may fetch 30–50% of book value. Equipment is often worth far less. The IBC recovery rates for Indian corporate defaults remain well below 100%.",
      "Ignoring contingent liabilities. Performance guarantees, letters of credit, and obligations on behalf of subsidiaries don't appear on the main balance sheet but can create sudden, large cash obligations. Always review the notes on contingent liabilities when conducting credit analysis.",
    ],
  },

  "reading-crisil-icra-moodys-reports": {
    readingTime: "8 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Credit Risk Fundamentals", href: "/learn/foundations/credit-analysis/credit-risk-fundamentals" },
      { label: "Solvency Ratios", href: "/learn/foundations/financial-statement-analysis/solvency-ratios" },
    ],
    intuition: `Credit rating agencies distil complex credit risk analysis into a simple alphabetical grade. A CRISIL AAA rating on an NCD tells a retail bond investor that CRISIL's analysts have assessed this company and believe default risk is minimal. This is enormously valuable — it enables millions of investors to participate in debt markets without doing their own deep credit analysis.\n\nThe largest Indian rating agencies are CRISIL (a S&P Global company), ICRA (a Moody's affiliate), CARE Ratings, and India Ratings (a Fitch company). Their methodologies are rigorous, their reports detailed, and their rating committees independent — in principle. In practice, ratings are lagged indicators; they often move after markets have already repriced the credit.\n\nReading a rating report carefully gives you the agency's view of key risks, financial metrics, industry position, and what would cause an upgrade or downgrade — a structured analytical framework that is useful even if you ultimately disagree with the rating.`,
    mechanics: `**Indian rating scales (long-term):**\n\n| Rating | Interpretation |\n|--------|---------------|\n| AAA | Highest safety |\n| AA+, AA, AA− | High safety |\n| A+, A, A− | Adequate safety |\n| BBB+, BBB, BBB− | Moderate safety (investment grade boundary) |\n| BB+, BB, BB− | Inadequate safety (speculative grade) |\n| B, C | High/very high default risk |\n| D | In default |\n\n**Outlook and Watch:**\n- **Outlook Stable/Positive/Negative:** Direction of rating over 12–24 months\n- **Rating Watch (Positive/Negative):** Imminent rating action likely within 3–6 months (often triggered by acquisition, restructuring, or regulatory change)\n\n**Key sections of a rating report:**\n1. **Rationale:** Why this rating, what are the key strengths and constraints\n2. **Key Rating Drivers:** The 3–5 factors that most influence the rating\n3. **Detailed Analysis:** Business risk (industry, competitive position), financial risk (leverage, coverage, liquidity)\n4. **Rating Sensitivity:** What would cause an upgrade/downgrade — very useful\n5. **Analytical Approach:** Standalone vs consolidated; group support considerations`,
    deepDive: `**Notching:** Rating agencies adjust ratings for structural subordination. If Holding Company A (rated AA) has a wholly-owned operating subsidiary B, bonds issued by A are typically notched down (e.g., AA−) because they are structurally subordinated to the obligations of B. The cash flows are generated at B; A depends on dividends or inter-company loans to service its own debt.\n\n**Group support and standalone ratings:** Some Indian companies receive uplift in their ratings because of expected parental or group support (e.g., a weaker subsidiary of a large conglomerate might be rated higher than its standalone financials justify). Conversely, some subsidiaries are "orphaned" by their groups when the parent itself is stressed.\n\n**Ratings lag markets:** The IL&FS group was rated AA+ by ICRA just weeks before it defaulted in September 2018. Markets had already started pricing distress in IL&FS debt before the rating action. Always watch bond yield spreads, CMDS (Credit Default Swaps for large companies), and stock price of holding companies alongside ratings.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Using ratings as investment signals. A rating of AAA says default risk is low, not that the bond is attractively priced. A BBB bond offering 200 bps more yield than a AAA bond may be the better investment if you believe the credit is mis-rated. Ratings are risk assessments, not recommendations.",
      "Ignoring the rating report for the rating. The report typically runs 8–15 pages with detailed financial analysis, industry outlook, and rating sensitivity. Reading only the grade misses the agency's analytical reasoning and the conditions that would trigger a change.",
      "Treating a stable outlook as permanent. Outlooks can shift within 12 months if circumstances change. Always check when the last rating action was and what triggered it. A 'stable' rating that hasn't been reviewed in 18 months during a turbulent period may be stale.",
    ],
  },

  "altman-z-score": {
    readingTime: "7 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Reading a Balance Sheet", href: "/learn/foundations/accounting/reading-a-balance-sheet" },
      { label: "Profitability Ratios", href: "/learn/foundations/financial-statement-analysis/profitability-ratios" },
      { label: "Credit Risk Fundamentals", href: "/learn/foundations/credit-analysis/credit-risk-fundamentals" },
    ],
    intuition: `In 1968, Edward Altman of New York University combined five financial ratios into a single score that predicted corporate bankruptcy with reasonable accuracy. The **Z-Score** became one of the most used quantitative tools in credit analysis because it translated pages of financial data into a single number.\n\nThe intuition behind it: companies that are heading for bankruptcy typically show up in their financials well before the event — declining profitability, rising leverage, shrinking retained earnings, poor liquidity. The Z-Score captures these signals and weights them based on their historical predictive power.\n\nWhile it was developed on US manufacturing data and requires calibration for Indian contexts, it remains a useful screening tool — especially for identifying companies where the score is deteriorating quickly over time, even if the absolute threshold doesn't translate directly.`,
    mechanics: `**Original Altman Z-Score (for public manufacturing companies):**\n\n\`Z = 1.2×X1 + 1.4×X2 + 3.3×X3 + 0.6×X4 + 1.0×X5\`\n\nWhere:\n- X1 = Working Capital ÷ Total Assets (liquidity)\n- X2 = Retained Earnings ÷ Total Assets (cumulative profitability / age)\n- X3 = EBIT ÷ Total Assets (operating profitability)\n- X4 = Market Value of Equity ÷ Book Value of Total Liabilities (market-based leverage)\n- X5 = Revenue ÷ Total Assets (asset efficiency)\n\n**Interpretation (original thresholds):**\n- Z > 2.99: Safe zone (low distress risk)\n- 1.81 < Z < 2.99: Grey zone\n- Z < 1.81: Distress zone (high default risk)\n\n**Variants:**\n- **Z'-Score:** For private companies (uses book value of equity in X4 instead of market value). Thresholds: > 2.6 safe, < 1.1 distress.\n- **Z''-Score:** For non-manufacturing / service companies (excludes X5, recalibrated coefficients). Better for Indian IT, pharma, FMCG companies.`,
    deepDive: `**Limitations for Indian application:** The Z-Score was calibrated on US data from the 1960s. Indian accounting standards, capital structure norms, and industry mix differ. Use it as a relative and trend indicator rather than applying the US thresholds literally.\n\n**The retained earnings trap:** X2 (Retained Earnings ÷ Assets) heavily penalises young, fast-growing companies that haven't had time to accumulate retained earnings. A profitable startup that is 3 years old will have low X2, inflating distress risk assessment. Use X2 trend (is it rising or falling?) rather than level.\n\n**Academic performance:** In Altman's original sample, the model correctly classified 94% of companies into bankrupt/non-bankrupt two years before actual bankruptcy. Predictive power degrades for longer horizons. More modern models (Ohlson O-Score, Zmijewski model) use logistic regression and may perform better in some contexts.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Applying the Z-Score to banks and financial companies. The Z-Score was designed for non-financial manufacturing companies. Banks have very different balance sheet structures (deposits are liabilities, loans are assets). Applying the Z-Score to HDFC Bank or ICICI Bank is not meaningful.",
      "Treating a Z-Score above 2.99 as risk-free. The model has error rates — both false positives (distress predicted but company survives) and false negatives (safe predicted but company defaults). It is a probabilistic screening tool, not a guarantee.",
      "Using a single year's score rather than the trend. A company with a Z-Score that has declined from 3.5 to 2.2 over three years is more concerning than one that has been stable at 2.0 for five years. Always plot the trend.",
    ],
  },

  "bond-pricing-and-yields": {
    readingTime: "10 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Time Value of Money", href: "/learn/foundations/corporate-finance/time-value-of-money" },
      { label: "Credit Risk Fundamentals", href: "/learn/foundations/credit-analysis/credit-risk-fundamentals" },
    ],
    intuition: `A bond is a loan in tradeable form. The borrower (issuer) promises to pay fixed interest (coupon) periodically and return the principal (face value) at maturity. The price at which this bond trades in the secondary market depends on how the current interest rate environment compares to the coupon and how risky the issuer is.\n\nThe critical relationship: **bond price and yield move in opposite directions**. If market interest rates rise after you buy a bond, your bond pays a lower coupon relative to new bonds — so its price falls to compensate. If rates fall, your bond looks attractive — its price rises.\n\nThis inverse relationship is the central mechanic of fixed income investing. Understanding it explains why RBI rate hikes cause bond prices to fall, and rate cuts cause them to rally — even though nothing changed about the bond's coupon payments.`,
    mechanics: `**Bond Pricing Formula:**\n\n\`P = Σ [C ÷ (1+y)^t] + [FV ÷ (1+y)^n]\`\n\nWhere: C = coupon payment, y = yield to maturity (YTM), n = number of periods, FV = face value\n\n**Example:** 3-year bond, face value ₹1,000, coupon 8% (paid annually), YTM 10%:\nP = 80/(1.10) + 80/(1.10)² + 1,080/(1.10)³ = 72.7 + 66.1 + 811.0 = **₹949.8** (below par — discount bond)\n\n**Key yield measures:**\n- **Coupon Rate:** Fixed contractual rate on face value\n- **Current Yield = Annual Coupon ÷ Market Price** (ignores capital gain/loss to maturity)\n- **YTM:** The single discount rate that equates PV of all future cash flows to market price — the most complete return measure\n- **Yield Spread:** YTM minus the G-sec yield of similar maturity — represents the credit risk premium\n\n**Par, premium, and discount:**\n- YTM = Coupon Rate → Price = Par\n- YTM > Coupon Rate → Price < Par (discount bond)\n- YTM < Coupon Rate → Price > Par (premium bond)`,
    deepDive: `**Duration:** Measures the sensitivity of bond price to yield changes. Modified Duration ≈ % price change for 1% yield change. A bond with modified duration of 5 will lose approximately 5% in price if yields rise 1%.\n\n\`Duration = Σ [t × (Cash Flow_t ÷ (1+y)^t)] ÷ Price\`\n\nLonger maturity and lower coupon bonds have higher duration (more price sensitivity).\n\n**Convexity:** Price-yield relationship is curved, not linear. Convexity captures this curvature — high convexity means price rises more when yields fall than it drops when yields rise. A desirable property.\n\n**Accrued Interest:** When a bond is bought between coupon dates, the buyer must compensate the seller for the portion of the coupon that has accrued since the last payment. Clean price (quoted) + Accrued Interest = Dirty price (what you actually pay).`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Confusing coupon rate with yield to maturity. A bond with 8% coupon bought at ₹950 has a YTM above 8% (because you also gain the ₹50 discount at maturity). The coupon rate is fixed; the yield depends on the market price you pay.",
      "Ignoring accrued interest when computing actual cost. If you buy a bond quoting at ₹980 but 3 months of coupon has accrued, you pay ₹980 + accrued interest. The quoted clean price is not the total cash outlay.",
      "Treating all bonds of the same maturity as having the same price risk. A zero-coupon bond and a high-coupon bond with the same maturity have very different durations — the zero coupon bond has far higher duration and price sensitivity to yield changes.",
    ],
    tryItHref: "/tools/present-value",
  },

  "covenants-and-triggers": {
    readingTime: "7 min read",
    lastReviewed: "July 2025",
    prerequisites: [
      { label: "Credit Risk Fundamentals", href: "/learn/foundations/credit-analysis/credit-risk-fundamentals" },
      { label: "Solvency Ratios", href: "/learn/foundations/financial-statement-analysis/solvency-ratios" },
    ],
    intuition: `When a lender extends a large loan, they don't just hand over the money and hope for the best. They impose contractual restrictions on the borrower — called covenants — to protect themselves. These covenants define rules the borrower must follow throughout the life of the loan. Violating them gives the lender the right to demand early repayment or take control of the situation.\n\nThink of covenants as a pre-agreed contract that says: "we'll lend you money, but if your financial health deteriorates beyond these specific thresholds, we have the right to intervene — before you actually default on a payment." This gives lenders early warning and recourse, reducing their loss in a deteriorating credit.\n\nFor equity analysts, monitoring covenant headroom is crucial. A company approaching a covenant breach is under significant pressure — it may be forced to sell assets, raise dilutive equity, or renegotiate terms that benefit lenders at the expense of shareholders.`,
    mechanics: `**Types of covenants:**\n\n**Financial Covenants (quantitative)**\n- *Net Debt/EBITDA ≤ X× (maintenance test, typically quarterly):* e.g., "Net Debt/EBITDA shall not exceed 4.5×"\n- *Interest Coverage ≥ X× (EBIT/Interest):* e.g., "ICR shall be no less than 2.5×"\n- *DSCR ≥ X×:* Used in project finance\n- *Net Worth ≥ ₹X Cr:* Ensures minimum equity cushion\n\n**Affirmative Covenants (things borrower must do)**\n- Maintain adequate insurance\n- Provide quarterly financial statements\n- Notify lenders of material adverse changes\n- Maintain key regulatory licences\n\n**Negative Covenants (things borrower cannot do without lender consent)**\n- Restrict additional borrowings above a threshold\n- Restrict asset sales above a threshold (negative pledge)\n- Restrict dividend payments if below leverage/coverage thresholds\n- Restrict acquisitions above a certain size\n- Restrict change of business\n\n**What happens on breach:**\n1. Waiver: Lenders waive the breach (often with a fee)\n2. Renegotiation: Covenants are reset, often with tighter margins\n3. Acceleration: Lenders declare the loan immediately due and payable`,
    deepDive: `**Covenant-lite (cov-lite) deals:** In buoyant credit markets (especially in global leveraged buyout markets), lenders sometimes accept only incurrence covenants (triggered only when the borrower actively does something, like taking on more debt) rather than maintenance covenants (tested every quarter). Indian market covenants have generally been tighter than global cov-lite standards, especially for bank lending.\n\n**Material Adverse Change (MAC) clause:** A MAC clause allows lenders to accelerate if there's a material adverse change in the borrower's financial condition, business, or prospects. These are notoriously hard to trigger in practice — courts generally require a very severe and lasting deterioration. However, the threat of invoking MAC keeps management alert.\n\n**Covenant analysis in practice:** When evaluating an investment, request the credit agreement (or NCD trust deed). Map out: (a) each financial covenant level, (b) the current ratio, (c) headroom to breach, and (d) what business scenario triggers a breach. Model the covenant tests under your base case and stress cases.`,
    commonMistakes: [
      "Ignoring the distinction between incurrence and maintenance covenants. Maintenance covenants are tested regularly and require the company to stay within limits at all times. Incurrence covenants are only triggered by an action. A company with only incurrence covenants has far more financial flexibility.",
      "Not stress-testing covenant headroom. Reporting 3.8× Net Debt/EBITDA against a 4.5× covenant sounds comfortable. But if EBITDA falls 20% in a downturn, Net Debt/EBITDA rises to 4.75× — a breach. Always test covenants under realistic stress scenarios.",
      "Assuming a covenant breach means immediate default. In practice, most covenant breaches trigger negotiation rather than immediate acceleration. However, the waiver process gives lenders leverage to extract fees, higher margins, or additional collateral. This is negative for equity holders.",
    ],
  },
};

